Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mortimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Mortemer in Seine-Maritime, France, so called from Old French <i>mort(e)</i> ‘dead’ + <i>mer</i> ‘sea’, probably referring to a stagnant pond or drained swamp.","Irish (of Norman origin): the Norman surname in sense 1 above was taken to Ireland from England in the medieval period, where it has also been adopted by bearers of the Gaelic surnames <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> and <b>ÓMuircheartaigh</b>, commonly Anglicized as <b>McMurty</b> and <b>Mortagh</b>. Compare   McMurdo  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mortimore","meanings":["English (Devon; of Norman origin): variant of   Mortimer  ."]},{"name":"McMurdo","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Muircheartaigh</b> or <b>Mac Muircheartaich</b>, ‘son of Muircheartach’, a personal name meaning ‘sea-ruler’. In Scotland the name was often lenited to give   McCurdy  . Compare   Murdoch   and   Moriarty  . The name was also used to Anglicize <i>Mac Murchaidh</i> (see   McMorrow  )."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":30,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margery de Mortimer was born in 1352, in Wigmore, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Philip Branch. She died on 30 November 1402, in Heaton, Lancashire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1352–30 Nov 1402":"1352–30. november 1402","1345–Male":"1345–Surnud","1374–1441":"1374–1441","1379–Male":"1379–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1352–1402":"1352–1402","1402":"1402","1379":"1379","30 Nov 1402":"30. november 1402","1345":"1345","1441":"1441","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Heaton, Lancashire, England":"Heaton, Lancashire, England","Ormesby, Cleveland, England, United Kingdom":"Cleveland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ormesby, Norfolk, England":"Ormesby St Michael, Norfolk, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Abingdon, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Abingdon, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1352–30 Nov 1402":"1352–30. marraskuuta 1402","1345–Male":"1345–Kuollut","1374–1441":"1374–1441","1379–Male":"1379–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1352–1402":"1352–1402","1402":"1402","1379":"1379","30 Nov 1402":"30. marraskuuta 1402","1345":"1345","1441":"1441","1352":"1352","1374":"1374","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Heaton, Lancashire, England":"Heaton, Lancashire, England","Ormesby, Cleveland, England, United Kingdom":"Cleveland, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ormesby, Norfolk, England":"Ormesby St Michael, Norfolk, England","Wigmore, Herefordshire, England":"Wigmore, 